If you are looking for a great book to read over the summer, you can check out this book "What If..." by John Flint. It is a fun-filled story about four children who get into a crazy adventure where they have to rescue a princess from garden gnomes. They get help from a brave knight and a powerful wizard. They have several challenges they have to overcome to complete their task.

Dear Parents/Guardians,

In an effort to prepare for possible extended closure, the West Central School District is looking for your feedback on resources you have available in the home for connecting to learning. If we are called to have school closure for an extended period of time, we intend to provide remote learning access for all of our students. This remote learning access will count as contact hours for your students, meaning that their attendance and participation in the work is required.

Please take the time to fill out the following survey (one survey per household) to help us cater instruction to your students. We would greatly appreciate if you could fill out this survey by 12:00pm tomorrow (3/17). If you are unable to fill out the form electronically please call the schools direct line at 605-528-6229. The line will be open from 5:00 PM – 9:00 PM today, March 16 and 8:00 AM to 12:00 PM March 17.

https://forms.gle/27qa2uBEDj5DH9ob9

COVID-19 Superintendent Update - 3:00pm

March 11th, 2020

3:00pm- West Central School District will be closed on Thursday, March 12th and Friday, March 13th. District facilities will be closed until Monday, March 16th. All activities, meetings, and practices are canceled through Sunday, March 15th.

While the South Dakota Department of Health has determined schools need not close, we are committed to completing a thorough cleaning of district facilities and transportation vehicles. School will resume on Monday, March 16th. The end of the 3rd quarter will now be Wednesday, March 18th.

This is the final announcement for today. Further updates will be sent as needed.

Brad Berens
West Central Superintendent

At 7:30am this morning, West Central School District administration met with county officials to discuss a district action plan in response to the report of a Hartford resident with school-age children testing positive for COVID-19. The adult male identified has not been on district property within the last week.

In consultation with the CDC, South Dakota Department of Health, the Governor’s Office, and local officials, an action plan has been developed to mitigate the potential spread of COVID-19. The district has initiated steps to deep clean all school buildings and sources of transportation. All district buildings are closed and all activities are canceled for today. This includes outside groups who have reserved facility space for Community Education and/or practices.

Please stay tuned to media outlets for further updates and information coming regularly throughout the day.

Brad Berens
West Central Superintendent

post_text: Students at Hartford Elementary had the opportunity to learn from Hartford firefighters and EMT’s for Fire Prevention Week! Kindergarteners were able to see the firefighters in their gear and learned how to be safe in case of a fire. First graders learned about the different equipment that firefighters and EMT’s use, as well as safety guidelines if there is a fire. Second graders had the opportunity to go through the Fire Safety House and learned about escape plans in case of a fire. A HUGE thank you to the Hartford Area Fire and Rescue for spending time with our students! They loved it!

post_text:
West Central’s Music Education Program Receives National Recognition

Hartford, SD- April 19, 2018 – West Central has been honored with the Best Communities for Music Education designation from The NAMM Foundation for its outstanding commitment to music education.

The Best Communities for Music Education designation is awarded to districts that demonstrate outstanding achievement in efforts to provide music access and education to all students.

This award recognizes that West Central is leading the way with learning opportunities as outlined in the Every Student Succeeds Act (ESSA). The legislation guides implementation in the states and replaces the No Child Left Behind Act (NCLB) which was often criticized for an overemphasis on testing-while leaving behind subjects such as music. ESSA recommends music and the arts as important elements of a wellrounded education for all children

post_text: West Central students competed in STEAM-based challenges that spotlight creativity, innovation, teamwork and collaboration skills at the Southeast Area Destination Imagination Regional tournament held at Tri-Valley school on Saturday, March 10th. Four West Central teams placed in the top three of their challenge division with three teams moving on and competing at state level in Pierre on Saturday, April 7th. In the elementary level, two West Central Teams placed first and will be moving on to the state tournament in Pierre. The “DI Crazy Snail Kids” tied for first place in the Fine Arts Challenge “Change of Tune”. The “Pink Pizza Pencil Trees” placed first in the Engineering Challenge “Drop Zone”.

post_text: We had a very exciting afternoon at Hartford Elementary! To celebrate our students making the 200 point PBIS goal, we had Opening Ceremonies for our Trojan Olympics! We had some special guests help us open up our Trojan Olympics. Some of the Sioux Falls Storm Lightning Girls helped welcome our Olympians into the ceremonies. Tyler Knight from the Sioux Falls Storm came and spoke to the students about what it takes to be a good teammate and a good student! Lastly, we were lucky to have five Trojan high school students join us to tell the students how they use good character in their lives, both academically and athletically! Thank you to all of our guests, and staff, for making it a great afternoon!

post_text: We had a special surprise yesterday at Hartford Elementary! Some of our classes reached their first quarter point goals for PBIS points, and they celebrated by having some Trojan athletes come and visit! The high schoolers read them books, talked with them about how they use their positive behavior in their sports and school, and some danced and played games with the students! A big 'Thank You!' to all of the student-athletes who took time out of their day to help us celebrate!

post_text:
I love it when we set out a new challenge and their brains just go crazy with excitement!
Makey Makey: An Invention Kit for Everyone, is an electronic invention tool and toy that allows users to connect everyday objects to computer programs.[1] Using a circuit board, alligator clips, and a USB cable, the toy uses closed loop electrical signals to send the computer either a keyboard stroke or mouse click signal. This function allows the Makey Makey to work with any computer program or webpage since all computer programs and webpages take keyboard and mouse click inputs.

A reminder that we have an election on Tuesday, September 27th to vote on a $500,000 opt out of the general fund property tax levy. Polls will be open from 7:00 AM to 7:00 PM at three different locations, the West Central Administrative Office in Hartford, the Humboldt Elementary Library, and the Wall Lake Township Hall.

For more information, you can find handouts on the main West Central webpage, http://www.westcentral.k12.sd.us.

Thanks for your participation.

The West Central School Board will be hosting a public forum to discuss an opt out of $500,000 of the general fund levies set by the state. You are welcome to attend on Wednesday, August 31st at 7:00 PM in the West Central High School Auditorium to learn more about this issue.

An election is scheduled for Tuesday, September 27th to decide whether or not the opt out is passed by the taxpayers in the West Central School District. We hope you can join us Wednesday to learn more about this important topic.
